{{Infobox organization | name = {{nowrap|Centre for the Study of Existential Risk}} | image = [[File:Centre for the Study of Existential Risk.svg|250px]] | formation = {{start date and age|2012}} | leader_title = Director | purpose = Higher Education and Research | headquarters = [[Cambridge]], [[England]] | founders = {{bulleted list | [[Huw Price]] | [[Martin Rees|Lord Martin Rees]] | [[Jaan Tallinn]] }} | parent_organization = [[University of Cambridge]] | homepage = {{URL|cser.ac.uk}} }}
[[File:Martin Rees-6Nov2005.jpg|thumb|British cosmologist and astrophysicist Martin Rees, former [[President of the Royal Society]] and co-founder of the CSER]]
The '''Centre for the Study of Existential Risk''' ('''CSER''') is a research centre at the [[University of Cambridge]], intended to study possible [[extinction-level threat]]s posed by present or future technology.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Biba|first1=Erin|title=Meet the Co-Founder of an Apocalypse Think Tank|url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/meet-the-co-founder-of-an-apocalypse-think-tank/|publisher=Scientific American|accessdate=2 July 2016|date=1 June 2015}}</ref> The co-founders of the centre are [[Huw Price]] (a philosophy professor at Cambridge), [[Martin Rees, Baron Rees of Ludlow|Martin Rees]] (a cosmologist, astrophysicist, and former [[President of the Royal Society]]) and [[Jaan Tallinn]] (a computer programmer and co-founder of [[Skype]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cam.ac.uk/research/news/humanitys-last-invention-and-our-uncertain-future/|title=Humanity's last invention and our uncertain future|last=Lewsey|first=Fred|date=25 November 2012|work=[[Research News]]|accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref> CSER's advisors include philosopher [[Peter Singer]], computer scientist [[Stuart J. Russell]], statistician [[David Spiegelhalter]], and cosmologist [[Max Tegmark]].<ref name=About_CSER/> Their "goal is to steer a small fraction of Cambridge’s great intellectual resources, and of the reputation built on its past and present scientific pre-eminence, to the task of ensuring that our own species has a long-term future."<ref name=About_CSER>{{cite web |url=http://cser.org/about/ |title=About CSER |publisher=Centre for the Study of Existential Risk |access-date=2014-05-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151212093559/http://cser.org/about/# |archive-date=2015-12-12 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref name="herald">{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=11124603 |title=Can We Survive?|work=The New Zealand Herald |first=Steve|last=Connor |date=14 September 2013}}</ref>
==Areas of focus== The centre's founding was announced in November, 2012.<ref>AP News, [https://www.yahoo.com/news/cambridge-study-technologys-risk-humans-190948884--finance.html Cambridge to study technology's risk to humans], 25 November 2012.</ref> Its name stems from Oxford philosopher [[Nick Bostrom]]'s concept of ''existential risk'', or risk "where an adverse outcome would either annihilate Earth-originating intelligent life or permanently and drastically curtail its potential".<ref name="bostrom">{{cite journal |last=Bostrom |first=Nick |date=2002 |title=Existential Risks: Analyzing Human Extinction Scenarios |url=http://www.nickbostrom.com/existential/risks.pdf |journal=Journal of Evolution and Technology |volume=9 |issue=1 |accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref> This includes technologies that might permanently deplete humanity's resources or block further scientific progress, in addition to ones that put the species itself at risk.
Among the [[global catastrophic risks]] to be studied by CSER are those stemming from possible future advances in artificial intelligence. The potential dangers of [[artificial general intelligence]] have been highlighted in early discussions of CSER, being likened in some press coverage to that of a robot uprising à la ''[[The Terminator]]''.<ref name="technorati">{{cite web|url=http://technorati.com/technology/article/risk-of-a-terminator-style-robot/|title=Risk of a Terminator Style Robot Uprising to be Studied|last=Gaskell|first=Adi|date=27 November 2012|work=[[Technorati]]|accessdate=2 December 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121130053807/http://technorati.com/technology/article/risk-of-a-terminator-style-robot/|archivedate=30 November 2012|df=}}</ref><ref name="guardian">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2012/dec/02/ai-robots-google-car-humans-john-naughton|title=Could robots soon add to mankind's existential threats?|last=Naughton|first=John|date=2 December 2012|work=[[The Observer]] |accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref> Price explained to the AFP news agency, "It seems a reasonable prediction that some time in this or the next century intelligence will escape from the constraints of biology". He added that when this happens "we're no longer the smartest things around," and will risk being at the mercy of "machines that are not malicious, but machines whose interests don't include us".<ref name="AP">{{cite web|last=Hui|first=Sylvia|title=Cambridge to study technology's risks to humans |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/cambridge-study-technologys-risk-humans |publisher=Associated Press |date=25 November 2012 |accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> Price has also mentioned [[synthetic biology]] as being dangerous because "[as a result of] new innovations, the steps necessary to produce a weaponized virus or other bioterror agent have been dramatically simplified" and that consequently “the number of individuals needed to wipe us all out is declining quite steeply.”<ref name="time">{{cite web|title = Rise of the machines: Cambridge University to study technology’s ‘existential risk’ to mankind |url = http://newsfeed.time.com/2012/11/29/rise-of-the-machines-cambridge-university-to-study-technologys-existential-risk-to-mankind/ |work = Time |date=29 November 2012 |accessdate=2 May 2014 |first=Kharunya|last=Paramaguru}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cser.org/emerging-risks-from-technology/developments-in-biotechnology/|title=Biological and Biotechnological Risks|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>
Other technologies CSER seeks to evaluate include [[molecular nanotechnology]],<ref name="cser-nanotech">{{cite web |url=http://cser.org/emerging-risks-from-technology/nanotechnology/ |title=Molecular nanotechnology |publisher=Centre for the Study of Existential Risk |accessdate=4 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503064234/http://cser.org/emerging-risks-from-technology/nanotechnology/# |archive-date=2014-05-03 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> extreme [[climate change]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cser.org/emerging-risks-from-technology/extreme-tail-climate-risks/|title=Extreme Climate Change|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref> and systemic risks from fragile networks.<ref name="ibtimes">{{cite web |url = http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/doomsday-list-cambridge-centre-study-existential-risk-505925 |title = Doomsday list for apocalypse: bioterrorism, cyber-attacks and hostile computers threaten mankind |first= Hannah|last = Osborne|work = International Business Times |date=13 September 2013 |accessdate = 2 May 2014}}</ref><ref name="cser-fragile">{{cite web |url=http://cser.org/emerging-risks-from-technology/systemic-risks-and-fragile-networks/ |title= Systemic risks and fragile networks |publisher=Centre for the Study of Existential Risk |accessdate = 2 May 2014}}</ref>
==Media coverage== CSER has been covered in many different newspapers (particularly in the United Kingdom),<ref name = "herald" /><ref name='technorati' /><ref name='guardian' /><ref name = "AP" /><ref name = "time" /><ref name='ibtimes' /><ref name="media page">{{cite web | url=http://cser.org/media-coverage | title=CSER media coverage | publisher=Centre for the Study of Existential Risk | accessdate=19 June 2014 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140630042953/http://cser.org/media-coverage/ | archivedate=30 June 2014 | df= }}</ref> mostly covering different topics of interest. University of Cambridge Research News' coverage of it focuses on risks from artificial general intelligence.<ref name=SFR>{{cite web | url= http://www.cam.ac.uk/research/news/humanitys-last-invention-and-our-uncertain-future | title = Humanity's Last Invention and Our Uncertain Future | work=University of Cambridge Research News}}</ref> The CSER was profiled in the special [[Frankenstein]] issue of ''Science'' in 2018. <ref name="ScienceMag">{{cite journal|url=http://science.sciencemag.org/content/359/6372/152|title=Taming the monsters of tomorrow||first1=Kai|last1=Kupferschmidt|journal=Science|date=2018-01-12|doi=10.1126/science.359.6372.152}}</ref> On existential risks to humanity, many scientists think the only serious one is the risk of global nuclear war. The Science article quoted [[Joyce Tait]] of the [[Imogen Institute]] in Edinburgh: "There is nothing [else] on the horizon." <ref name="ScienceMag"/>
