'''Coccas''' ({{lang-el|Κόκκας}}, died 552) was an [[Eastern Roman Empire|Eastern Roman]] soldier who deserted to the [[Ostrogothic Kingdom|Ostrogoths]] during the final stages of the [[Gothic War (535–554)|Gothic War]]. [[Procopius]] calls him "a Roman soldier" and "a man of the Gothic army".{{sfn|Amory|2003|p=368}} His name is not [[Germanic languages|Germanic]], and might be [[Thracian language|Thracian]].{{sfn|Amory|2003|p=368}}
Coccas was part of Ostrogothic king [[Totila]]'s army at the [[Battle of Taginae]] in June/July 552. He is described as a cavalryman of great physical strength. In order to gain time for the arrival of 2,000 reinforcements led by [[Teia]], Coccas rode towards the Romans and requested them to send forth a champion to engage him in [[single combat]]. [[Anzalas]], an [[Armenians|Armenian]] retainer of the Roman commander [[Narses]], accepted the challenge. Coccas charged at Anzalas and aimed at his stomach, but at the last moment, Anzalas swerved his horse and stabbed Coccas in the side, mortally wounding him.{{sfn|Bury|1958|p=265}} Although Coccas' sacrifice gained him the necessary time for the arrival of Teia, Totila died in the ensuing battle, which was a disaster for the Goths.{{sfn|Bury|1958|pp=265ff.}}
